So glad this is being recorded.

20
00:00:52,055 --> 00:00:55,597
All right, so I'm Nick Suttner.

21
00:00:55,717 --> 00:00:57,339
I'm a writer, designer, consultant.

22
00:00:57,899 --> 00:01:00,201
I'm gonna give you a decent bit of background on myself,

23
00:01:00,881 --> 00:01:02,703
but hopefully you'll see why that's important

24
00:01:02,723 --> 00:01:03,763
and how it leads into this topic.

25
00:01:05,814 --> 00:01:09,756
So, like a lot of people, I started working in games in retail around 2004.

26
00:01:10,756 --> 00:01:16,019
I had a lot of first-hand customer experience there, championing games,

27
00:01:16,999 --> 00:01:19,220
and it felt like being on the front lines of the industry.

28
00:01:19,820 --> 00:01:22,722
And sometimes I feel like I've sort of only gotten further from that in my career,

29
00:01:22,762 --> 00:01:23,802
which is a weird feeling.

30
00:01:25,813 --> 00:01:27,114
I handled this highlight on the corner there.

31
00:01:28,275 --> 00:01:30,977
That's Shadow of the Colossus, that's the PS4 remake,

32
00:01:31,037 --> 00:01:32,418
but back with the original release,

33
00:01:33,078 --> 00:01:34,940
I got the most pre-orders of Shadow of the Colossus

34
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:36,781
in my district, because I was a champion for the game.

35
00:01:36,821 --> 00:01:37,862
I loved telling people about it.

36
00:01:39,583 --> 00:01:40,644
And there was an interesting experience

37
00:01:40,664 --> 00:01:41,904
where people would come in and they'd say,

38
00:01:42,445 --> 00:01:43,526
what's cool, what should I play,

39
00:01:43,566 --> 00:01:45,127
especially people that didn't buy a lot of games.

40
00:01:45,587 --> 00:01:47,428
And I had the opportunity to walk over to the shelf

41
00:01:47,648 --> 00:01:48,909
and grab something and say, like,

42
00:01:48,969 --> 00:01:49,850
you should play this thing.

43
00:01:49,870 --> 00:01:51,131
And they would come back two weeks later.

44
00:01:51,751 --> 00:01:53,752
and say, oh, that was awesome, what else do you have?

45
00:01:53,792 --> 00:01:54,952
Which is a pretty rare experience,

46
00:01:55,012 --> 00:01:55,953
and I really enjoyed that,

47
00:01:55,993 --> 00:01:57,433
and that was maybe my first taste

48
00:01:58,594 --> 00:02:00,815
of being able to sort of recommend things,

49
00:02:00,895 --> 00:02:01,915
and I got a taste for it.

50
00:02:02,236 --> 00:02:04,356
I also had a gaming blog at the time

51
00:02:04,396 --> 00:02:06,537
with my friend Tom McShay, who's sitting back there,

52
00:02:07,458 --> 00:02:09,599
who has that in his face, he's not in here.

53
00:02:09,659 --> 00:02:13,660
But, and that's what sort of helped get me to my first E3,

54
00:02:13,720 --> 00:02:14,821
and I got more interested in it,

55
00:02:15,361 --> 00:02:16,722
and moved out to California here in 2007.

56
00:02:19,185 --> 00:02:23,446
I got my first industry job writing for EGM magazine, which I had grown up reading, and

57
00:02:23,466 --> 00:02:24,546
writing for 1up.com.

58
00:02:25,126 --> 00:02:30,208
And this was my first cover story, which also ended up being the last issue of EGM, so I

59
00:02:30,468 --> 00:02:31,408
guess I killed the magazine.

60
00:02:34,068 --> 00:02:39,190
And while I was there, though, at 1up especially, I reviewed a lot of games for those outlets,

61
00:02:39,370 --> 00:02:43,691
especially some of the early seminal indie games on Xbox Live and PlayStation Network.

62
00:02:44,471 --> 00:02:48,592
And I got comfortable championing smaller, more interesting games, and championing them

63
00:02:48,632 --> 00:02:49,513
came naturally to me.

64
00:02:50,513 --> 00:02:56,055
And I'll make a note here of N Plus and Braid, two of my favorite games, and I'll bring those

65
00:02:56,115 --> 00:02:56,615
up again later.

66
00:03:00,576 --> 00:03:02,337
If you're dying to read these, you can read them later on.

67
00:03:02,477 --> 00:03:03,897
Well, I don't know if there's a lot left, actually.

68
00:03:04,617 --> 00:03:05,598
One up sort of comes and goes.

69
00:03:07,150 --> 00:03:09,510
So I moved over to PlayStation in 2007,

70
00:03:09,751 --> 00:03:11,011
and I worked there for seven years.

71
00:03:11,771 --> 00:03:14,132
Started in product evaluation and worked with big publishers

72
00:03:14,212 --> 00:03:16,673
like Rockstar and Activision, but I was always the happiest

73
00:03:16,693 --> 00:03:18,313
when I got to work with independent developers.

74
00:03:19,354 --> 00:03:21,254
And I was vocal about the games I cared about,

75
00:03:21,294 --> 00:03:23,495
and people got to know me as sort of a content expert

76
00:03:23,575 --> 00:03:26,716
in that space, and as an advocate for smaller games.

77
00:03:28,012 --> 00:03:29,333
And I became the lead account manager

78
00:03:29,353 --> 00:03:31,416
in developer relations on that team.

79
00:03:31,456 --> 00:03:32,837
I worked with hundreds of developers

80
00:03:33,098 --> 00:03:34,419
and helped make indie games a part

81
00:03:34,439 --> 00:03:35,981
of the PlayStation culture in a bigger way,

82
00:03:36,041 --> 00:03:38,203
especially leading up to the PlayStation 4 launch.

83
00:03:39,064 --> 00:03:40,947
I signed a lot of games while I was at PlayStation.

84
00:03:41,868 --> 00:03:42,388
All these ones.

85
00:03:43,244 --> 00:03:46,589
and a bunch more, and I worked with all of those devs

86
00:03:46,609 --> 00:03:47,790
to help them release their game,

87
00:03:48,050 --> 00:03:50,273
and served as an advocate within Sony

88
00:03:50,293 --> 00:03:51,154
throughout the process.

89
00:03:51,715 --> 00:03:54,419
And I spent tens of hours, and sometimes hundreds of hours

90
00:03:54,539 --> 00:03:55,840
on each of these games of work,

91
00:03:55,861 --> 00:03:58,003
so it was a lot of my time spent on this stuff.

92
00:03:59,284 --> 00:04:01,825
And again, here I'll call out The Witness and N++,

93
00:04:01,845 --> 00:04:05,306
both sort of the sequels or spiritual sequels

94
00:04:06,327 --> 00:04:08,367
to things before that I'd championed in the press.

95
00:04:09,208 --> 00:04:10,808
And so I'd sort of gotten to those developers

96
00:04:10,848 --> 00:04:13,189
and so those relationships were sort of mutually beneficial.

97
00:04:15,850 --> 00:04:18,511
And then I moved over to Oculus in 2016.

98
00:04:19,071 --> 00:04:20,511
I worked there for about 14 months,

99
00:04:21,372 --> 00:04:23,812
again, advocating for smaller, more experimental games,

100
00:04:24,453 --> 00:04:26,453
and found out that a lot of the same challenges exist

101
00:04:26,513 --> 00:04:28,454
for developers in VR, like visibility.

102
00:04:29,201 --> 00:04:32,604
Especially when most press aren't really covering VR in a meaningful way yet.

103
00:04:35,247 --> 00:04:39,170
I also along the way wrote a couple books on the work of Fumito Ueda while I was working

104
00:04:39,210 --> 00:04:39,931
those day jobs.

105
00:04:41,372 --> 00:04:44,815
And if you remember when I was a champion for Shadow of the Colossus back in my EB Games

106
00:04:44,835 --> 00:04:48,238
days, well it became my favorite game and my book is basically a love letter to it.

107
00:04:48,818 --> 00:04:52,502
So I used to have to champion games one by one at the store, and by this point I had

108
00:04:52,542 --> 00:04:55,284
a larger platform to speak from to champion something that I loved.

109
00:04:58,122 --> 00:04:59,242
And now I'm a game developer.

110
00:05:00,083 --> 00:05:03,725
I've actually been independent myself for longer than I worked at Oculus, which is weird

111
00:05:03,745 --> 00:05:05,045
because I guess I wasn't there too long.

112
00:05:05,105 --> 00:05:08,667
But this is a shot from a board game prototype I'm working on.

113
00:05:10,268 --> 00:05:12,269
But I'm working as a writer and an editor.

114
00:05:12,289 --> 00:05:15,731
I contributed to Celeste and Guacamelee 2 and Escape.

115
00:05:16,291 --> 00:05:20,534
I've done consulting work for a bunch of developers, including several that I work with at PlayStation.

116
00:05:20,554 --> 00:05:24,456
I'm also an advisor on Untitled Goose Game.

117
00:05:26,065 --> 00:05:27,765
I just wanted an excuse to put a big goose in here.

118
00:05:28,566 --> 00:05:32,147
And also working on a few of my own game projects and writing some upcoming games and doing

119
00:05:32,187 --> 00:05:33,208
biz dev for a few of them.

120
00:05:35,168 --> 00:05:36,929
So you know a bit about my background.

121
00:05:37,489 --> 00:05:44,312
I've been a champion across retail and in the press and at PlayStation and at Oculus

122
00:05:44,633 --> 00:05:45,033
and in print.

123
00:05:47,496 --> 00:05:49,838
And there's really others like me at every big company.

124
00:05:49,878 --> 00:05:51,239
There's people who care about interesting,

125
00:05:51,319 --> 00:05:54,781
artful, diverse games across PC and mobile

126
00:05:54,881 --> 00:05:56,082
and VR and console.

127
00:05:57,783 --> 00:05:59,625
And if you only remember one thing from my talk,

128
00:06:00,045 --> 00:06:01,026
it should probably be this.

129
00:06:01,206 --> 00:06:03,547
It's that companies don't care about your games,

130
00:06:03,848 --> 00:06:04,928
people care about your games.

131
00:06:07,999 --> 00:06:10,641
And you might ask why this distinction is really important,

132
00:06:10,681 --> 00:06:12,202
and this is sort of the whole point of my talk.

133
00:06:13,303 --> 00:06:15,244
Developers often ask these questions.

134
00:06:15,284 --> 00:06:17,366
They ask, will Microsoft care about my game?

135
00:06:17,846 --> 00:06:19,327
Why does Nintendo care about my game?

136
00:06:19,387 --> 00:06:20,988
How can I get Sony to feature my game?

137
00:06:21,729 --> 00:06:22,829
And I think these are really just

138
00:06:22,869 --> 00:06:24,210
fundamentally the wrong questions.

139
00:06:27,052 --> 00:06:28,694
Really the right question you should be asking yourself

140
00:06:28,754 --> 00:06:30,135
is who will help fight for my game?

141
00:06:31,247 --> 00:06:36,651
Because really I believe that any promotion, support, or funding of your game happens because somebody cares about it.

142
00:06:37,112 --> 00:06:39,333
This is true of platforms, publishers, press.

143
00:06:39,914 --> 00:06:45,238
People often refer to Sony's like indie program, and there was never a program really. Nothing formalized.

144
00:06:45,258 --> 00:06:46,879
It was just people who cared about indie games.

145
00:06:48,420 --> 00:06:51,382
And I should say too, by the way, this talk isn't about getting your game funded,

146
00:06:51,542 --> 00:06:54,945
but I think finding your champion is also a critical first step towards funding.

147
00:06:57,802 --> 00:06:59,983
And this talk also might feel sort of like Video Games 101

148
00:07:00,844 --> 00:07:02,485
to someone who's released a successful game

149
00:07:02,505 --> 00:07:03,986
and seen the results of this sort of thing,

150
00:07:04,407 --> 00:07:05,847
but for everyone else, I think its importance

151
00:07:05,888 --> 00:07:07,008
really can't be overstated.

152
00:07:07,028 --> 00:07:12,812
And also, this was the best image I found

153
00:07:12,832 --> 00:07:14,253
when I looked for Video Games 101,

154
00:07:14,734 --> 00:07:17,055
because I like the bold choice of intercapping video games.

155
00:07:18,676 --> 00:07:20,117
And it's a kid's YouTube channel,

156
00:07:20,137 --> 00:07:22,779
so you probably should like and subscribe and comment on it.

157
00:07:24,246 --> 00:07:28,469
And also, though, even I should say for experienced or successful indies, I think you can always

158
00:07:28,489 --> 00:07:29,450
use a reminder of this.

159
00:07:29,950 --> 00:07:32,912
And your game probably sold well because you made a great game, but somewhere along the

160
00:07:32,952 --> 00:07:36,335
way someone else had to fight for it and chose to promote it.

161
00:07:38,256 --> 00:07:39,838
And also this talk is not just for indies.

162
00:07:39,958 --> 00:07:41,339
AAA needs their champions too.

163
00:07:41,799 --> 00:07:44,421
They might have an easier starting point, but they still need someone to fight for them

164
00:07:44,481 --> 00:07:45,942
internally, and I've seen this firsthand.

165
00:07:48,975 --> 00:07:51,923
So sustainable game development isn't just about making your game.

166
00:07:52,966 --> 00:07:57,859
So many developers focus on making a great game and then don't spend the time telling people about it.

167
00:07:58,924 --> 00:08:01,106
Oh, by the way, I forgot to tell you to silence your phones

168
00:08:01,166 --> 00:08:03,268
and please fill out the evaluation afterwards,

169
00:08:03,348 --> 00:08:04,629
but you're gonna do that anyways.

170
00:08:05,990 --> 00:08:08,893
So sometimes developers don't even tell

171
00:08:08,953 --> 00:08:10,574
their launch platform about the game really,

172
00:08:10,594 --> 00:08:12,616
and they just submit it to certification when it's done,

173
00:08:12,776 --> 00:08:13,917
which seems crazy to me.

174
00:08:15,178 --> 00:08:17,420
And a lot of developers just don't even upload a video

175
00:08:17,440 --> 00:08:18,661
with their game, and you have to ask

176
00:08:18,741 --> 00:08:21,063
why a storefront would be excited to promote a game

177
00:08:21,604 --> 00:08:22,725
when people are gonna have a hard time

178
00:08:22,765 --> 00:08:23,625
finding out more about it.

179
00:08:24,806 --> 00:08:26,007
I tweeted this recently, I said,

180
00:08:26,047 --> 00:08:27,387
if you don't have a trailer ready to launch

181
00:08:27,427 --> 00:08:28,808
alongside your game on the storefront,

182
00:08:28,828 --> 00:08:31,208
you're not ready to release your game full stop.

183
00:08:32,189 --> 00:08:33,189
And I had a couple of people saying

184
00:08:33,209 --> 00:08:34,150
that they just didn't have time

185
00:08:34,170 --> 00:08:35,270
while they were finishing their game,

186
00:08:35,370 --> 00:08:37,491
and to me, you really shouldn't consider your game finished

187
00:08:37,511 --> 00:08:38,831
until you're ready to launch it properly,

188
00:08:38,871 --> 00:08:40,112
that's all part of the process.

189
00:08:40,672 --> 00:08:42,232
And you shouldn't really be committing your date

190
00:08:42,292 --> 00:08:43,753
to fans or a publisher,

191
00:08:44,413 --> 00:08:46,574
because I think having all of this ready

192
00:08:46,654 --> 00:08:47,714
should dictate your date,

193
00:08:47,794 --> 00:08:50,255
not just release based on when the game

194
00:08:50,275 --> 00:08:50,936
is gonna be finished.

195
00:08:53,389 --> 00:08:56,091
And games almost never do well purely organically.

196
00:08:56,511 --> 00:08:58,132
Sometimes people just don't show up to buy them.

197
00:08:59,352 --> 00:09:01,133
And some developers feel like releasing a game

198
00:09:01,173 --> 00:09:03,214
on a console is enough to have decent sales,

199
00:09:03,414 --> 00:09:04,915
and I can tell you that that's not right.

200
00:09:06,296 --> 00:09:08,637
And sometimes games go viral and word of mouth is enough,

201
00:09:08,697 --> 00:09:09,798
but you can never count on that,

202
00:09:09,818 --> 00:09:11,258
so you should never plan for it.

203
00:09:11,619 --> 00:09:13,520
The rest of the time, you really do need a champion

204
00:09:13,540 --> 00:09:15,941
to help connect a great game to its potential fans.

205
00:09:18,263 --> 00:09:21,226
And once a game has a bad launch, it's much harder to get future promotion.

206
00:09:21,727 --> 00:09:24,370
And it makes sense, because why would a storefront want to repromote something

207
00:09:24,390 --> 00:09:26,412
that didn't make them any money the first time around?

208
00:09:26,452 --> 00:09:28,073
That's really their primary goal.

209
00:09:28,093 --> 00:09:33,579
So I'm going to talk about how platforms work.

210
00:09:33,639 --> 00:09:36,382
My background is primarily on the platform side, so that's going to be my focus.

211
00:09:36,402 --> 00:09:38,484
And we'll touch a bit on publishers and press later.

212
00:09:39,185 --> 00:09:41,027
But a lot of this is relevant to working with them as well.

213
00:09:41,959 --> 00:09:44,081
And this is also relevant for finding champions, I think,

214
00:09:44,121 --> 00:09:46,625
who are streamers or YouTubers and non-traditional marketing

215
00:09:46,665 --> 00:09:47,526
and PR channels.

216
00:09:47,606 --> 00:09:49,088
But that'll be a different talk.

217
00:09:49,108 --> 00:09:53,293
So I'm going to give you sort of an overview of how platforms

218
00:09:53,353 --> 00:09:53,794
are set up.

219
00:09:54,795 --> 00:09:57,078
Content teams are typically the game experts.

220
00:09:57,499 --> 00:09:58,340
Oh, wait, sorry.

221
00:09:58,380 --> 00:09:59,641
Hold on, let's talk about those first.

222
00:10:01,334 --> 00:10:03,375
Yeah, so we have the sort of promotional teams.

223
00:10:04,735 --> 00:10:06,796
And so we have the store teams at a platform,

224
00:10:06,956 --> 00:10:10,517
marketing teams, PR and social teams, the events teams.

225
00:10:11,037 --> 00:10:13,278
And then we have a content group sort of separately.

226
00:10:13,298 --> 00:10:15,958
And those people are the game experts basically

227
00:10:15,998 --> 00:10:18,939
across consoles, PC, mobile, VR, this is true everywhere.

228
00:10:18,959 --> 00:10:21,260
These are basically what you would call third party

229
00:10:21,360 --> 00:10:23,440
or developer relations, product evaluation,

230
00:10:23,480 --> 00:10:25,741
account management, that's usually the same thing.

231
00:10:26,601 --> 00:10:28,542
And that's where your champion is going to reside.

232
00:10:30,655 --> 00:10:35,039
And promotion often goes, those people go to the content people and they say,

233
00:10:35,079 --> 00:10:36,960
OK, what games are cool? What should we be featuring?

234
00:10:36,980 --> 00:10:38,441
What should we be talking about on the platform?

235
00:10:38,861 --> 00:10:41,303
And the content team says, well, it's probably Ape Out,

236
00:10:41,323 --> 00:10:42,864
because that's an amazing game.

237
00:10:43,907 --> 00:10:45,108
And so that's what we should feature this week

238
00:10:45,148 --> 00:10:46,369
and talk about on all of our channels.

239
00:10:46,889 --> 00:10:48,631
And people running digital storefronts

240
00:10:48,711 --> 00:10:50,552
tend to be experts at running storefronts,

241
00:10:50,633 --> 00:10:51,834
but probably not at games.

242
00:10:53,195 --> 00:10:54,296
And the people working at the storefronts,

243
00:10:54,376 --> 00:10:56,638
usually their goals, their KPIs,

244
00:10:56,698 --> 00:10:58,099
are to make the most money every day.

245
00:10:58,199 --> 00:10:59,660
So they're going to default to promoting

246
00:10:59,700 --> 00:11:01,402
the most reliable things in the biggest games

247
00:11:01,442 --> 00:11:03,444
that are already successful and already making money.

248
00:11:04,485 --> 00:11:05,606
So it's up to the content people

249
00:11:05,686 --> 00:11:07,687
to sort of help steer that and tell them about new stuff

250
00:11:07,707 --> 00:11:10,210
that they should consider promoting as an alternate.

251
00:11:13,252 --> 00:11:16,435
And every time there's an event at a GDC or an E3 or wherever,

252
00:11:17,536 --> 00:11:20,018
the events team is going to ask the content team what games they should feature.

253
00:11:20,098 --> 00:11:23,821
So again, that's going to come back to that same champion helping feature your game at an event.

254
00:11:25,599 --> 00:11:28,440
And these are also the same groups who are going to promote your game out into the world,

255
00:11:28,540 --> 00:11:30,260
and ideally they should be doing most of the work.

256
00:11:31,181 --> 00:11:34,722
The caveat being that you can't really ever rely on any of these things, so you still

257
00:11:34,782 --> 00:11:38,983
should plan on doing as much promotion as possible yourself, and that platforms don't

258
00:11:39,003 --> 00:11:42,844
really tend to create promotions from scratch, but they'll very often boost your signal.

259
00:11:45,520 --> 00:11:47,361
You know, Apple has a store editorial team as well.

260
00:11:47,401 --> 00:11:49,143
You should submit great assets with your game.

261
00:11:49,203 --> 00:11:52,846
They care a lot about how your games make their platform look.

262
00:11:53,106 --> 00:11:56,829
I assume Google and Stadia are also going to have some sort of storefront, and if it

263
00:11:56,849 --> 00:11:59,431
does, I can pretty much guarantee this is going to hold true there as well.

264
00:12:01,332 --> 00:12:04,154
Steam still makes editorial decisions about what to promote.

265
00:12:04,514 --> 00:12:08,337
Even if a lot of it ends up being algorithmic, those first few hours of your launch can make

266
00:12:08,377 --> 00:12:09,718
a huge difference and be really important.

267
00:12:11,259 --> 00:12:13,139
And all these organizations are full of people.

268
00:12:13,920 --> 00:12:17,781
Everyone has their own tastes and likes and dislikes and their own priorities.

269
00:12:18,821 --> 00:12:22,763
You know, a caveat being that there's different ranges of skills and empowerment and not everyone

270
00:12:22,783 --> 00:12:25,784
can help you as much as everyone else and sometimes you have to find the right person.

271
00:12:26,844 --> 00:12:30,966
And some platforms are more automated than others and still ask you to, you know, email

272
00:12:31,026 --> 00:12:34,227
an alias instead of a person, but there's always people at the other end of those aliases

273
00:12:34,287 --> 00:12:36,088
and you can still do your best to connect with someone.

274
00:12:38,389 --> 00:12:44,493
So briefly, just for some context, these were my priorities I felt like when I was working at the big platforms.

275
00:12:46,874 --> 00:12:50,276
My first priority was to the players, to sort of share cool games to more people.

276
00:12:53,518 --> 00:12:56,760
And then to developers, to have them have a good experience with the platform.

277
00:12:58,559 --> 00:13:00,441
And then to myself, really, in my own career,

278
00:13:00,541 --> 00:13:02,622
and what I sort of wanted to make that into,

279
00:13:02,762 --> 00:13:03,963
or how this all affected me.

280
00:13:04,344 --> 00:13:05,444
And then, really, to my platform.

281
00:13:05,504 --> 00:13:08,407
Like, I didn't fundamentally care about Sony's bottom line.

282
00:13:09,067 --> 00:13:09,487
Why would I?

283
00:13:10,848 --> 00:13:12,550
I still, I'm a huge, you know, I grew up with PlayStation.

284
00:13:12,590 --> 00:13:13,570
I'm a huge fan of the platform,

285
00:13:13,590 --> 00:13:15,232
and I want to make their storefront an awesome place,

286
00:13:15,432 --> 00:13:17,633
but, you know, these were sort of roughly my priorities.

287
00:13:17,693 --> 00:13:21,036
I really, you know, I genuinely was more interested

288
00:13:21,076 --> 00:13:22,937
in a good experience for players and developers

289
00:13:22,977 --> 00:13:24,739
than maybe myself, with the platforms being less.

290
00:13:24,799 --> 00:13:25,980
And this is true everywhere I've gone.

291
00:13:26,920 --> 00:13:32,462
And honestly, I think this is what made me good at my job when I was at these places because I cared more about my work than the job itself.

292
00:13:33,562 --> 00:13:39,484
And I think my point here is that your priorities probably align a lot more with biz dev people than you think they might,

293
00:13:39,904 --> 00:13:43,865
because they really do genuinely care about your games and success, often over their own platform.

294
00:13:47,991 --> 00:13:51,092
And also I should say you don't really have to be a partner title to benefit from this.

295
00:13:51,272 --> 00:13:53,233
You don't have to have a formalized agreement with the platform.

296
00:13:53,773 --> 00:13:58,735
You know, even if you come out first on PlayStation and later on Xbox or first on mobile and later on PC,

297
00:13:58,755 --> 00:14:01,296
you know, a champion can still help you with those things.

298
00:14:01,936 --> 00:14:06,097
And typically, you know, there's less reason to promote a later release on a platform.

299
00:14:06,617 --> 00:14:11,539
And therefore this can be just as important, if not more so, you know, if not more important on an eventual platform

300
00:14:11,559 --> 00:14:12,760
that might end up making you more money.

301
00:14:13,798 --> 00:14:17,459
And I'll say too, if a platform ever offers you money of any sort, even if it's a small amount,

302
00:14:17,559 --> 00:14:21,600
you should probably take it, because the extra support there is gonna be, you know, that'll be the real win,

303
00:14:21,660 --> 00:14:24,541
because that leads to so many more promotions and opportunities.

304
00:14:24,981 --> 00:14:29,303
You know, these platforms tend to have sort of buckets, where any game that they're partnering with

305
00:14:29,343 --> 00:14:33,584
or funding even a small amount is that sort of the first priority, and then everything else.

306
00:14:33,924 --> 00:14:36,645
So even taking a small amount of money can make you a much higher priority,

307
00:14:36,665 --> 00:14:41,186
and the, you know, the long-term dividends of that can be much more important than the money that you took.

308
00:14:43,966 --> 00:14:45,507
I didn't know quite how to do this,

309
00:14:45,547 --> 00:14:46,568
and this was a late slide,

