00:18:00,238 --> 00:18:04,739
So Zach was talking about making a game that people want to play now, especially, to be

377
00:18:04,759 --> 00:18:06,860
able to participate in the conversation around a game.

378
00:18:07,400 --> 00:18:11,781
And if we go back and we look at those Something New games that I pulled out, I think there

379
00:18:11,801 --> 00:18:15,902
is a certain zeitgeist around them that's really true to that idea, and they weren't

380
00:18:15,942 --> 00:18:20,102
known quantities, and that's part of what made them really true discussion pieces, and

381
00:18:20,122 --> 00:18:21,703
that can be a huge factor in success.

382
00:18:23,119 --> 00:18:27,403
And again, all ties back to giving your champion reasons

383
00:18:27,423 --> 00:18:28,123
to want to fight for you.

384
00:18:29,825 --> 00:18:32,267
I believe that a screenshot should sell your game.

385
00:18:32,287 --> 00:18:34,189
This is Inside, of course, by Playdead.

386
00:18:34,209 --> 00:18:35,991
It's beautiful, evocative.

387
00:18:36,211 --> 00:18:37,012
It makes me want to play it.

388
00:18:37,092 --> 00:18:39,214
But not everyone has six years to polish a game

389
00:18:39,234 --> 00:18:40,595
and make incredible lighting.

390
00:18:42,157 --> 00:18:43,798
This is Plug and Play by Etter Studio.

391
00:18:43,998 --> 00:18:46,280
And sometimes simpler things can be just as intriguing.

392
00:18:46,321 --> 00:18:48,022
I don't know what it is, but I want to play it.

393
00:18:49,447 --> 00:18:54,259
This is Prune by Polyculture. It's sort of a less-delayed example, but this is simple, beautiful color,

394
00:18:54,279 --> 00:18:55,903
it's intriguing, makes me want to know more about it.

395
00:18:58,090 --> 00:18:59,891
And if your game is hard for you to describe,

396
00:18:59,931 --> 00:19:01,532
it's gonna be hard for your champion as well.

397
00:19:01,972 --> 00:19:03,993
And they probably won't be excited to be your champion,

398
00:19:04,033 --> 00:19:05,374
not because they're not excited about the game,

399
00:19:05,394 --> 00:19:06,634
but because it's gonna be too difficult

400
00:19:06,674 --> 00:19:09,035
and they're gonna run into too many roadblocks internally

401
00:19:09,055 --> 00:19:10,336
when they're trying to talk about your game.

402
00:19:11,957 --> 00:19:12,717
Salt and Sanctuary.

403
00:19:12,777 --> 00:19:15,998
So I don't think that the best game pitches are really

404
00:19:16,078 --> 00:19:17,479
it's this thing meets this other thing.

405
00:19:17,519 --> 00:19:19,040
And I think that usually means your game

406
00:19:19,080 --> 00:19:20,380
is not unique enough to stand out.

407
00:19:21,001 --> 00:19:23,723
However, it's still better than being able to describe,

408
00:19:23,783 --> 00:19:26,265
you know, to not describe it or talk about why it's unique.

409
00:19:26,685 --> 00:19:28,867
And Salt and Sanctuary really has an easy pitch.

410
00:19:29,648 --> 00:19:30,769
Stark Souls in 2D.

411
00:19:30,849 --> 00:19:32,991
And I don't think I actually overtly said that,

412
00:19:33,071 --> 00:19:34,832
but that's what was clear from when I played it.

413
00:19:35,873 --> 00:19:37,994
And it has a great demo and a team I wanted to work with.

414
00:19:38,214 --> 00:19:41,316
Really, it was a no-brainer for me to sign and work with.

415
00:19:41,896 --> 00:19:46,959
And as a counter-example, there was a lot of discussion about why Tacoma didn't maybe sell as well as expectations at launch,

416
00:19:46,979 --> 00:19:49,381
despite great reviews and being from the Gone Home team.

417
00:19:49,881 --> 00:19:53,303
And for me, just in my opinion, a big reason of that might have been that you...

418
00:19:53,663 --> 00:19:56,945
To me, you could never really tell what the experience of the game was when you were watching a trailer.

419
00:19:57,766 --> 00:20:01,269
I didn't really know what sort of gameplay it was gonna be,

420
00:20:01,569 --> 00:20:02,991
and I had to play it to appreciate the game,

421
00:20:03,031 --> 00:20:05,193
and I love the game, but I had to play it to find that out.

422
00:20:05,873 --> 00:20:07,134
And I'd actually also argued that

423
00:20:07,575 --> 00:20:09,357
Where the Water Tastes Like Wine had the same issue.

424
00:20:09,377 --> 00:20:11,799
It was hard to watch a trailer and really understand

425
00:20:11,959 --> 00:20:13,420
what the gameplay experience was gonna be.

426
00:20:18,545 --> 00:20:20,127
So your champion really has to believe

427
00:20:20,187 --> 00:20:21,988
you're capable of making the games that you wanna make.

428
00:20:23,836 --> 00:20:29,060
I think if you say you're going to make the next Apex Legends, then it's not going to

429
00:20:29,080 --> 00:20:30,281
go anywhere because you're probably not.

430
00:20:30,901 --> 00:20:34,023
But if you say you're going to make the next Stardew Valley, with enough time maybe you

431
00:20:34,063 --> 00:20:37,246
can, who knows if it'll be successful, but you can probably accomplish something of that

432
00:20:37,286 --> 00:20:37,566
scope.

433
00:20:38,987 --> 00:20:42,469
And I think having examples is really important, even if you haven't made a successful game

434
00:20:42,509 --> 00:20:42,669
yet.

435
00:20:42,709 --> 00:20:46,192
Just showing that you're able of making anything is much better than nothing.

436
00:20:47,153 --> 00:20:52,576
And also I should note that your champion really only cares about the concepts of your game, not really how the game turns out.

437
00:20:53,017 --> 00:20:55,118
I think that's usually true actually when people are funding things.

438
00:20:55,178 --> 00:20:59,141
So I don't think you should feel pressure to deliver exactly the thing you're showing them up front.

439
00:21:01,028 --> 00:21:03,249
And knowing when to show your game I think is important too,

440
00:21:03,289 --> 00:21:04,249
especially when you're pitching.

441
00:21:05,090 --> 00:21:06,710
This is something actually that Tyler Sigmund

442
00:21:06,770 --> 00:21:09,491
of Red Hook Studios, who did Darkest Dungeon, reminded me.

443
00:21:10,671 --> 00:21:13,092
You know, basically if you're making the next No Man's Sky,

444
00:21:13,612 --> 00:21:16,413
then you're fine to show your game at an early concept stage.

445
00:21:17,253 --> 00:21:18,334
But if it needs to be something

446
00:21:18,354 --> 00:21:19,614
that needs to be proven out further,

447
00:21:19,654 --> 00:21:20,874
you should wait until you have a demo

448
00:21:20,894 --> 00:21:22,075
to showcase the game well.

449
00:21:22,795 --> 00:21:23,875
And this is sort of a paradox

450
00:21:23,975 --> 00:21:26,036
because you might need publisher support earlier,

451
00:21:26,176 --> 00:21:27,856
but you might be more likely to get it later

452
00:21:27,937 --> 00:21:29,257
if you can wait until when you show the game

453
00:21:29,297 --> 00:21:30,157
at the right point in time.

454
00:21:32,042 --> 00:21:36,426
Something else to consider, maybe don't post programmer or placeholder art online before

455
00:21:36,466 --> 00:21:38,187
release if it's going to change significantly.

456
00:21:38,267 --> 00:21:39,468
It might come back to haunt you.

457
00:21:40,469 --> 00:21:42,310
If you're going to use placeholders, make them obvious.

458
00:21:42,891 --> 00:21:47,574
Chris Hecker told me that the art director on Spore would put big pink triangles in screenshots

