00:22:51,409 --> 00:22:53,090
and so we put a lot of value in face time.

481
00:22:53,490 --> 00:22:56,011
And we've always sort of assumed that by showing up at events like this

482
00:22:56,051 --> 00:22:57,192
and making time for meetings,

483
00:22:57,532 --> 00:22:59,553
we're communicating commitment to the platform as well,

484
00:22:59,653 --> 00:23:03,235
which I feel is totally the case.

485
00:23:03,695 --> 00:23:05,856
So just relax, talk to everyone at these events.

486
00:23:06,097 --> 00:23:09,759
They're not just an opportunity to meet fans and potential fans of your game,

487
00:23:10,099 --> 00:23:11,740
but really with potential business partners too.

488
00:23:12,331 --> 00:23:15,673
You can sell a few copies by staffing a booth

489
00:23:15,713 --> 00:23:16,514
and hanging out with your game.

490
00:23:16,634 --> 00:23:17,814
Meeting the right business person

491
00:23:17,834 --> 00:23:19,436
and having the right meeting can unlock

492
00:23:19,476 --> 00:23:20,837
selling tens of thousands of copies.

493
00:23:21,657 --> 00:23:23,539
And I think it's important to talk to everyone

494
00:23:23,859 --> 00:23:26,521
at a platform or not, specifically,

495
00:23:26,621 --> 00:23:27,962
don't talk to people who aren't business people

496
00:23:28,722 --> 00:23:29,923
and not just the business people

497
00:23:30,263 --> 00:23:32,245
because even event staff, PR,

498
00:23:32,625 --> 00:23:34,226
other people can become your champion as well.

499
00:23:34,286 --> 00:23:37,589
And if someone from Nintendo PR loves your game,

500
00:23:37,629 --> 00:23:38,849
then your other Nintendo champion

501
00:23:38,869 --> 00:23:40,110
will have a lot less work to do

502
00:23:40,150 --> 00:23:41,311
when it gets to the PR stage.

503
00:23:42,592 --> 00:23:45,655
I would always take it pretty seriously when someone from another department at PlayStation

504
00:23:45,675 --> 00:23:47,176
would say, hey, have you checked out this game?

505
00:23:47,196 --> 00:23:51,119
Especially if I didn't know about it already, because we can't possibly see everything.

506
00:23:51,179 --> 00:23:52,600
So I would always put stock in that.

507
00:23:54,762 --> 00:23:56,503
And other developers can be your champions too.

508
00:23:56,523 --> 00:24:00,346
This is like not great pictures of the indie megabooth online somehow, but...

509
00:24:01,565 --> 00:24:03,907
You know, the community, your community is very,

510
00:24:04,128 --> 00:24:05,990
my community, our community, is very supportive

511
00:24:06,030 --> 00:24:07,812
and good things can come just from

512
00:24:07,832 --> 00:24:09,073
having casual conversations.

513
00:24:10,014 --> 00:24:11,736
Developers might share press lists with each other,

514
00:24:11,836 --> 00:24:13,418
contacts, other helpful connections,

515
00:24:13,899 --> 00:24:15,120
and maybe you can even find someone else

516
00:24:15,140 --> 00:24:16,482
to collaborate with or connections

517
00:24:16,522 --> 00:24:17,583
with artists and musicians.

518
00:24:18,764 --> 00:24:23,325
And also if a highly respected developer recommends another developer to a platform that can go a long way.

519
00:24:24,026 --> 00:24:26,547
Dan Edelman, who used to do biz dev at Nintendo,

520
00:24:27,067 --> 00:24:31,929
he told me that this whole chain of people, Kyle Gabler from World of Goo, introduced Edmund McMillan,

521
00:24:32,269 --> 00:24:35,510
made Super Meat Boy to Dan, and then Edmund introduced Derek Yu, who made Spelunky.

522
00:24:35,570 --> 00:24:39,692
So it's this whole chain where, you know, if you have a good relationship with a platform,

523
00:24:40,152 --> 00:24:43,653
they'll take your advice seriously. So this networking can have these great knock-on effects.

524
00:24:45,595 --> 00:24:48,777
This is the JW Marriott hotel lobby during E3,

525
00:24:48,837 --> 00:24:49,677
also not great pictures,

526
00:24:49,757 --> 00:24:51,958
but this is where a lot of the business gets done at E3.

527
00:24:52,878 --> 00:24:55,279
And you've, I'm sure, experienced some of this around GDC.

528
00:24:55,319 --> 00:24:56,879
Hotel lobbies, bars, coffee shops

529
00:24:56,899 --> 00:24:58,060
are all great places to meet people

530
00:24:58,100 --> 00:24:59,700
and have sort of more personal conversations.

531
00:25:00,101 --> 00:25:02,341
And even if you can't afford a pass to a show,

532
00:25:02,361 --> 00:25:04,142
a lot of them are still worth going to

533
00:25:04,282 --> 00:25:06,243
just for the networking, like GDC, obviously.

534
00:25:07,962 --> 00:25:11,024
This is my old laptop from, this is like a sheet of stickers

535
00:25:11,044 --> 00:25:13,486
that I peeled off from when I worked at PlayStation.

536
00:25:14,007 --> 00:25:15,688
Because I actually do believe in like, you know,

537
00:25:15,808 --> 00:25:16,989
if you meet a platform representative,

538
00:25:17,029 --> 00:25:17,970
give them something small.

539
00:25:18,130 --> 00:25:19,391
If you have it, give them a cool sticker,

540
00:25:19,811 --> 00:25:21,833
a business card that has a code to download

541
00:25:22,293 --> 00:25:23,314
your game or your demo.

542
00:25:23,875 --> 00:25:25,796
Nothing big, but I still have this

543
00:25:25,856 --> 00:25:28,538
and I'm a nostalgic person, but it's a cool thing

544
00:25:28,578 --> 00:25:30,160
and I don't know, I'm weird.

545
00:25:32,460 --> 00:25:33,861
Remember people's names.

546
00:25:34,341 --> 00:25:36,082
It sounds obvious, but you won't find a champion

547
00:25:36,102 --> 00:25:37,323
by seeming like you don't care.

548
00:25:37,343 --> 00:25:39,925
Always reintroduce yourself with your game,

549
00:25:40,505 --> 00:25:42,386
with the name of your game, I should say.

550
00:25:42,987 --> 00:25:44,888
It really helps your champion to associate the two

551
00:25:44,908 --> 00:25:46,549
because they're meeting a ton of people all the time.

552
00:25:47,009 --> 00:25:49,011
Don't be offended if they forget your name

553
00:25:49,071 --> 00:25:50,292
because, again, they're meeting a lot of people.

554
00:25:52,120 --> 00:25:56,524
And even better than an event is going and visiting an office of a platform.

555
00:25:56,844 --> 00:25:59,366
If you have a contact already, I'd say offer to go visit them.

556
00:25:59,466 --> 00:26:01,247
I think it's always worth it.

557
00:26:01,608 --> 00:26:04,010
Tell them you're coming to town, you'd like to come by and present your game.

558
00:26:04,110 --> 00:26:05,691
I think they're often likely to accept.

559
00:26:05,771 --> 00:26:08,854
It's nice to just say, oh, sorry, I can't do my regular work.

560
00:26:08,874 --> 00:26:11,076
I'm going to go have lunch with the developer this afternoon.

561
00:26:12,657 --> 00:26:14,298
And it's a much better context to see a game in.

562
00:26:14,338 --> 00:26:15,900
It'll be a lot more memorable for them as well.

563
00:26:17,496 --> 00:26:18,637
Hopefully you know about Presskit,

564
00:26:19,497 --> 00:26:20,278
something else that really helps

565
00:26:20,298 --> 00:26:21,359
with making your game findable.

566
00:26:22,440 --> 00:26:25,302
Presskit's by Rami Ismail of Flumbeer

567
00:26:25,582 --> 00:26:26,563
and some other good folks.

568
00:26:26,583 --> 00:26:27,644
You should really be using it.

569
00:26:28,805 --> 00:26:30,806
This is gonna help you get some basic facts up

570
00:26:30,826 --> 00:26:32,788
about your company if you have one in your game.

571
00:26:33,228 --> 00:26:35,230
Make sure you have your contact info listed online,

572
00:26:35,250 --> 00:26:37,992
which sounds obvious, but you'd be surprised.

573
00:26:38,953 --> 00:26:41,335
And a personal contact is better than a generic one.

574
00:26:41,415 --> 00:26:43,336
So I think nick at company.com

575
00:26:43,376 --> 00:26:45,138
is better than info at company.com.

576
00:26:45,678 --> 00:26:50,003
It might feel more professional that way, but it feels like screaming into a void otherwise.

577
00:26:50,043 --> 00:26:51,625
And it really does drive me crazy.

578
00:26:51,985 --> 00:26:55,889
It drives me crazy how many games don't have websites or a trailer online.

579
00:26:55,950 --> 00:26:59,534
Don't make your game hard to find. Make sure the name of your game is Googlable.

580
00:26:59,894 --> 00:27:01,556
And if you're lucky, someone might be looking for you.

581
00:27:03,736 --> 00:27:05,878
I think being persistent is good in this case.

582
00:27:07,240 --> 00:27:11,624
And as far as reaching out to your platform and trying to stay on their radar,

583
00:27:12,124 --> 00:27:14,707
DevRelations folks get hundreds of emails every day,

584
00:27:15,207 --> 00:27:16,548
and so checking in often helps.

585
00:27:17,389 --> 00:27:18,831
It keeps you near the top of their mind.

586
00:27:19,311 --> 00:27:22,034
Personalize your emails. Don't just put people on a generic mailing list.

587
00:27:22,674 --> 00:27:23,915
And keep your emails concise.

588
00:27:24,156 --> 00:27:27,198
Include a video or a GIF, something moving for them to see.

589
00:27:31,625 --> 00:27:34,247
Don't send email blasts to everybody that you know at a company.

590
00:27:34,687 --> 00:27:38,950
This is a way you can maybe get an important problem solved quickly, which is important

591
00:27:38,990 --> 00:27:40,911
sometimes but it's not going to help you find your champion.

592
00:27:42,773 --> 00:27:45,735
If you can't go to events or don't have a contact somewhere, you can check on Twitter.

593
00:27:46,135 --> 00:27:48,857
Again everyone is just people, they're probably going to respond to you and if they can't

594
00:27:48,897 --> 00:27:52,059
help directly, they're probably going to send you to whoever can or whomever can.

595
00:27:54,767 --> 00:27:58,753
So we talked about making the right game, making yourself findable, and then you need

596
00:27:58,773 --> 00:28:01,557
to give your champion the best tools to help you to find your game.

597
00:28:06,992 --> 00:28:08,333
So we're gonna talk about arming your champion.

598
00:28:09,713 --> 00:28:12,215
So a big part of this is sending thoughtful demos

599
00:28:12,255 --> 00:28:13,256
when you send a game somewhere.

600
00:28:14,857 --> 00:28:16,478
I'd say that Steam keys are ideal,

601
00:28:16,578 --> 00:28:19,000
better than a standalone build probably, but not essential.

602
00:28:20,561 --> 00:28:21,722
If you have a dev kit already,

603
00:28:21,782 --> 00:28:23,023
sending a build on their hardware

604
00:28:23,043 --> 00:28:24,884
shows that you're sort of serious about the platform

605
00:28:24,904 --> 00:28:25,764
and that helps a lot.

606
00:28:27,706 --> 00:28:29,526
If a game is planned to have controller support,

607
00:28:29,546 --> 00:28:31,067
you should have controller support in your demo.

608
00:28:31,127 --> 00:28:33,667
The only game that I managed to not get funded at Sony

609
00:28:33,687 --> 00:28:35,128
that I really wanted to and fought for

610
00:28:35,168 --> 00:28:37,028
was because they didn't have controller support yet

611
00:28:37,108 --> 00:28:38,269
in their demo, and so it was hard

612
00:28:38,709 --> 00:28:39,969
to extrapolate the experience.

613
00:28:41,330 --> 00:28:43,050
And don't make people have to read separate documents.

614
00:28:43,330 --> 00:28:45,991
It's better to mock up a simple control instruction screen

615
00:28:46,031 --> 00:28:47,251
and put it at the front of your demo.

616
00:28:48,292 --> 00:28:50,572
I'd also say a YouTube link is always better

617
00:28:50,592 --> 00:28:51,673
than an attached video.

618
00:28:51,773 --> 00:28:53,713
It makes it easier for people to share around internally.

619
00:28:54,856 --> 00:28:57,041
And if you provide a private YouTube link, you can track the views.

620
00:28:57,061 --> 00:28:57,983
You can see if they shared it.

621
00:28:58,003 --> 00:28:59,607
Maybe you can, like, guilt them into watching it.

622
00:29:01,291 --> 00:29:03,777
And I would say beware if you're making, like, a multiplayer game.

623
00:29:05,703 --> 00:29:06,863
Developers making a multiplayer game

624
00:29:06,883 --> 00:29:09,644
would sometimes try to schedule me times

625
00:29:09,684 --> 00:29:11,025
to play their game online with them,

626
00:29:11,065 --> 00:29:12,545
and it never really went quite well,

627
00:29:12,585 --> 00:29:14,206
especially when you're trying to fill a room of people.

628
00:29:14,926 --> 00:29:16,747
And it also means your champion might not

629
00:29:16,767 --> 00:29:18,047
be able to show it at events, since it's

630
00:29:18,087 --> 00:29:19,488
going to require multiple stations.

631
00:29:19,568 --> 00:29:21,529
So again, make multiplayer games,

632
00:29:21,569 --> 00:29:22,649
but just be aware of those challenges

633
00:29:22,709 --> 00:29:24,670
when you're trying to find people to champion them.

634
00:29:27,231 --> 00:29:28,371
Yeah, make it self-contained.

635
00:29:29,412 --> 00:29:30,192
And some things I can share.

636
00:29:30,212 --> 00:29:30,972
I talked about those already.

637
00:29:31,032 --> 00:29:33,493
So research their platforms as well.

638
00:29:35,247 --> 00:29:37,928
Be aware of any similarities to other first party games

639
00:29:37,948 --> 00:29:39,809
that are coming, that they're developing themselves.

640
00:29:41,450 --> 00:29:42,670
Be familiar with their storefront,

641
00:29:42,710 --> 00:29:43,831
just passingly familiar even.

642
00:29:43,871 --> 00:29:45,792
You'd be surprised how many people I'd be in meetings with

643
00:29:45,832 --> 00:29:48,673
and would not really know how the PlayStation store worked

644
00:29:48,993 --> 00:29:50,174
because they just hadn't used it.

645
00:29:52,115 --> 00:29:54,116
And think about their priorities as well.

646
00:29:54,156 --> 00:29:55,917
Does the company have a new peripheral coming out?

647
00:29:55,937 --> 00:29:57,317
Can you support it in a cool way?

648
00:29:57,537 --> 00:29:59,518
That's sort of the ultimate ammunition for your champion

649
00:29:59,538 --> 00:30:00,839
if that's something you can do, of course,

650
00:30:00,879 --> 00:30:02,200
without shoehorning it into your...

651
00:30:04,321 --> 00:30:06,902
And this is true of publishers as well.

652
00:30:06,922 --> 00:30:09,603
You should know their lineup, you should know their taste, so you're not pitching them something

653
00:30:09,643 --> 00:30:11,664
that is just not a good fit from the start.

654
00:30:16,026 --> 00:30:18,267
Your personal story can be just as important as your game.

655
00:30:18,848 --> 00:30:21,609
Knowing about your situation, your team, this will help people remember you.

656
00:30:21,629 --> 00:30:24,690
Do you have a unique development story, a unique background?

657
00:30:24,950 --> 00:30:27,792
Your champions are going to tell your story for you when they talk about the game.

658
00:30:29,863 --> 00:30:32,525
The story of Axiom Verge was a big part of why I was able to sign it.

659
00:30:33,045 --> 00:30:36,827
The developer, Tom Happ, had a day job at a bigger studio and worked on his passion

660
00:30:36,847 --> 00:30:38,868
project at night, one that he'd had in mind for years.

661
00:30:39,289 --> 00:30:42,471
And we could help him have a bit more freedom to focus on the game.

662
00:30:42,511 --> 00:30:44,032
We knew that the game was going to turn out great.

663
00:30:44,772 --> 00:30:49,455
And I'd also say the story of your game, don't confuse this point with the actual literal

664
00:30:49,535 --> 00:30:50,515
narrative story of the game.

665
00:30:51,456 --> 00:30:52,677
The setting of your game is plenty.

666
00:30:52,717 --> 00:30:55,478
People really won't care about the larger story of your game.

667
00:30:55,999 --> 00:30:56,659
When you're pitching it.

668
00:30:56,699 --> 00:30:59,402
And I'm sad to say that as a writer, but it's true.

669
00:31:01,884 --> 00:31:04,407
And think about really talking about why you're making this game.

670
00:31:04,667 --> 00:31:08,911
Companies can only fund so many games and you can only make so many games in your life.

671
00:31:09,792 --> 00:31:10,813
Why did you choose this game?

672
00:31:10,853 --> 00:31:12,014
Why are you the one to make it?

673
00:31:12,114 --> 00:31:14,917
Not your relevant experience, but your personal motivation.

674
00:31:15,398 --> 00:31:18,561
I think that's part of your story and what people will respond to and pay attention to

675
00:31:18,601 --> 00:31:19,301
when you talk about it.

676
00:31:20,917 --> 00:31:23,538
A lot of developers have asked me this, they say,

677
00:31:23,578 --> 00:31:24,418
what are you looking for?

678
00:31:25,499 --> 00:31:26,919
And I think, again, that's the wrong question.

679
00:31:26,959 --> 00:31:29,540
If you think about everything we've discussed,

680
00:31:29,580 --> 00:31:31,521
people are just looking for projects that get them excited.

681
00:31:31,581 --> 00:31:32,561
It's just a personal thing.

682
00:31:33,201 --> 00:31:34,502
If anything, what aren't you looking for

683
00:31:34,562 --> 00:31:35,902
is an easier question to answer.

684
00:31:36,262 --> 00:31:38,063
Maybe they have a lot of one genre already

685
00:31:38,263 --> 00:31:39,864
or know that they have trouble getting

686
00:31:39,904 --> 00:31:41,124
certain types of games supported.

687
00:31:42,741 --> 00:31:47,486
I think being specific is actually better than being flexible when you're pitching.

688
00:31:48,027 --> 00:31:51,630
I think you want to provide very specific budget and timeline breakdowns.

689
00:31:51,650 --> 00:31:54,953
You don't want to give people a menu of options of different sort of compromised versions

690
00:31:54,993 --> 00:31:58,157
of the game you could make for this amount of money, but I'd rather make this version

691
00:31:58,177 --> 00:31:59,178
of the game for this amount of money.

692
00:31:59,638 --> 00:32:02,901
It might feel counterintuitive, but really I'd say you should pitch the version of the

693
00:32:02,921 --> 00:32:03,882
game that you want to make.

694
00:32:04,042 --> 00:32:06,184
I think that's the version that's most likely to get signed.

695
00:32:07,586 --> 00:32:14,353
I was actually just right before this talk, I was meeting up with Matt Dixon, who's a director of business development at EA,

696
00:32:14,914 --> 00:32:20,599
and he said this verbatim without me prompting him. He basically said, yeah, you should pitch the game you want to make,

697
00:32:20,619 --> 00:32:24,143
because that's what's going to get funded. And I was like, oh, that's in my talk. I'm going to say your name.

698
00:32:26,093 --> 00:32:27,054
Think about shared goals.

699
00:32:27,214 --> 00:32:28,554
Every platform has their own goals.

700
00:32:28,974 --> 00:32:30,455
For instance, with mobile,

701
00:32:30,635 --> 00:32:32,755
how nice might your game make their hardware look?

702
00:32:33,096 --> 00:32:34,996
Nintendo has a strong heritage of platformers,

703
00:32:35,076 --> 00:32:36,977
Microsoft of shooting games and racing games,

704
00:32:37,037 --> 00:32:38,217
and Sony with art games.

705
00:32:39,237 --> 00:32:40,778
Maybe there's an annual seasonal promotion

706
00:32:40,818 --> 00:32:41,518
you can align with.

707
00:32:41,598 --> 00:32:43,639
Maybe they need to launch a new feature you can support.

708
00:32:44,079 --> 00:32:45,919
I think framing the conversation that way is good.

709
00:32:45,959 --> 00:32:49,540
How can my game release best support PlayStation?

710
00:32:51,641 --> 00:32:52,681
And for subsequent launches,

711
00:32:52,741 --> 00:32:55,082
second, third, distant launches.

712
00:32:56,570 --> 00:32:58,992
You know, adding new game content is helpful.

713
00:32:59,032 --> 00:33:00,673
Maybe there's a new game mode you can add.

714
00:33:01,294 --> 00:33:02,655
Maybe it's just some new costumes.

715
00:33:02,715 --> 00:33:05,057
Maybe all the DLC is now included in the main game.

716
00:33:05,317 --> 00:33:07,159
You know, give people a hook.

717
00:33:07,799 --> 00:33:09,240
Make them a new trailer for the new platform.

718
00:33:09,260 --> 00:33:11,022
Cut a new trailer and make new assets for them

719
00:33:11,062 --> 00:33:13,004
so it can feel special and unique for their platform.

720
00:33:14,167 --> 00:33:16,748
Consider platform-specific features, like we talked about,

721
00:33:16,768 --> 00:33:19,330
if there's a way you can support that without too much work.

722
00:33:19,890 --> 00:33:21,151
And treat them like your first launch.

723
00:33:21,171 --> 00:33:23,473
You don't want to feel like a second-class citizen on a platform,

724
00:33:23,493 --> 00:33:25,094
and you shouldn't make them feel that way either.

725
00:33:25,754 --> 00:33:27,475
And the more serious you take subsequent launches,

726
00:33:27,515 --> 00:33:29,437
the more seriously those platforms are going to take you,

727
00:33:29,477 --> 00:33:32,178
and then that release gap of time will start to matter less.

728
00:33:33,963 --> 00:33:35,224
So we talked about making the right game,

729
00:33:35,265 --> 00:33:37,627
making yourself findable, arming your champion,

730
00:33:38,548 --> 00:33:40,229
and really you wanna keep your champion around

731
00:33:40,269 --> 00:33:43,713
for a long time, from when you put it on the radar

732
00:33:43,733 --> 00:33:45,374
to when it comes out and well beyond that,

733
00:33:46,075 --> 00:33:47,156
and then on to your next game.

734
00:33:50,067 --> 00:33:52,788
Your champion should always have access to the latest major build of your game,

735
00:33:53,728 --> 00:33:56,349
that has new features and polish, it doesn't need to be small iterative builds.

736
00:33:57,590 --> 00:34:01,272
And if it wasn't a Steam build that you can push updates to,

737
00:34:01,512 --> 00:34:03,813
just give them a link to a folder where you can keep the latest build,

738
00:34:05,053 --> 00:34:09,995
the latest assets, trailers, screenshots, and all of your contact info, your phone number.

739
00:34:10,336 --> 00:34:12,317
You never know when someone wants to call you up with an opportunity.

740
00:34:14,064 --> 00:34:16,346
I'd say trust your champion in my experience.

741
00:34:16,866 --> 00:34:21,248
If they don't need to ask you permissions for small things, more opportunities will open up.

742
00:34:21,768 --> 00:34:25,631
Flexible and willing and trusted developers really get the most ubiquitous support.

743
00:34:26,051 --> 00:34:30,173
And if you're sort of difficult to work with or precious about your games and these opportunities,

744
00:34:30,593 --> 00:34:33,695
people just skip you over to save time, even if it's a great game.

745
00:34:33,715 --> 00:34:35,716
They're just going to want to work with the games that are easiest.

746
00:34:37,066 --> 00:34:41,130
You know, your champion might need to go argue with their legal team on a contract,

747
00:34:41,170 --> 00:34:44,353
and I think that's okay because really, again, I think they're on your side most of the time.

748
00:34:45,814 --> 00:34:48,557
And similarly, don't, you know, you need to choose your battles.

749
00:34:48,577 --> 00:34:51,119
So don't push back on things that your champion said won't happen,

750
00:34:51,159 --> 00:34:52,681
just accept it and move on to the next thing,

751
00:34:52,741 --> 00:34:55,283
and think that they might genuinely have your best interests in mind.

752
00:34:57,158 --> 00:34:59,339
Learn organizations and their tool sets.

753
00:34:59,559 --> 00:35:01,280
Don't just email your champion about everything.

754
00:35:01,320 --> 00:35:03,461
If they've introduced you to another department to work with,

755
00:35:03,921 --> 00:35:05,822
then email that person and CC your champion.

756
00:35:06,362 --> 00:35:08,563
For example, well, I've been gone long enough,

757
00:35:08,583 --> 00:35:09,364
I don't know if it's true now,

758
00:35:09,404 --> 00:35:12,725
but DevNet used to be sort of the backend

759
00:35:13,005 --> 00:35:14,966
tech support message board stuff at Sony.

760
00:35:14,986 --> 00:35:16,267
There's a learning curve up front,

761
00:35:16,287 --> 00:35:19,248
but that's the place to get your questions answered quickly

762
00:35:19,268 --> 00:35:20,429
and then just asking your champion

763
00:35:20,469 --> 00:35:22,210
is gonna end up sending you back there.

764
00:35:23,288 --> 00:35:25,790
Don't announce anything without checking with your champion first.

765
00:35:26,110 --> 00:35:28,512
You might be excited to share things publicly throughout development,

766
00:35:28,532 --> 00:35:29,913
but always check in with your champion.

767
00:35:30,354 --> 00:35:32,375
They might have an opportunity you don't know about.

768
00:35:32,776 --> 00:35:36,339
Always give them the opportunity to debut the news or boost your signal

769
00:35:36,359 --> 00:35:38,841
because a lot of times they won't do it if you already have.

770
00:35:38,861 --> 00:35:41,022
It's sort of less exciting on their channel as if it's old news.

771
00:35:41,703 --> 00:35:44,605
And maybe even try talking to platforms before you announce a game.

772
00:35:45,266 --> 00:35:47,007
It's sort of more fun for them to be able to announce

773
00:35:47,107 --> 00:35:49,289
and that unlocks bigger opportunities a lot of the time.

774
00:35:50,554 --> 00:35:52,876
And that's a defer to your champion on your launch date.

775
00:35:52,896 --> 00:35:53,496
Think about that.

776
00:35:54,397 --> 00:35:56,038
Don't choose a release date and then ask them

777
00:35:56,078 --> 00:35:57,299
if they can support that date.

778
00:35:57,359 --> 00:35:59,180
Defer to whatever date they say is best,

779
00:35:59,440 --> 00:36:00,581
because this is gonna make you eligible

780
00:36:00,621 --> 00:36:02,002
for more promotions and support.

781
00:36:02,482 --> 00:36:04,344
And they can often warn you away from bad dates,

782
00:36:04,384 --> 00:36:05,424
even if they can't tell you why.

783
00:36:05,484 --> 00:36:07,866
Like, hey, there's a big game launching on that date.

784
00:36:07,886 --> 00:36:09,067
You should probably push back a few weeks.

785
00:36:13,130 --> 00:36:17,693
So, this one's sort of about saying thank you.

786
00:36:19,575 --> 00:36:22,517
So consider sending them something nice

787
00:36:22,698 --> 00:36:23,939
when they help with the milestones.

788
00:36:23,979 --> 00:36:26,061
I think it really is worth the cost, like tenfold.

789
00:36:26,101 --> 00:36:28,783
So Axiom Verge, Tom Hap sent me a couple gift baskets

790
00:36:28,803 --> 00:36:30,485
when we signed the game and at release.

791
00:36:30,965 --> 00:36:33,307
The Star Wars guys sent me a $100 Starbucks gift card.

792
00:36:33,327 --> 00:36:34,228
That was really nice of them,

793
00:36:34,248 --> 00:36:35,369
and I'll always remember those things,

794
00:36:35,429 --> 00:36:36,290
and it meant a lot to me.

795
00:36:36,810 --> 00:36:38,031
It doesn't need to be anything decadent,

796
00:36:38,131 --> 00:36:39,713
and most companies have a gifting policies

797
00:36:39,753 --> 00:36:41,494
of what they can accept, but even a small thing

798
00:36:41,795 --> 00:36:43,336
to say thank you really goes a long way with them

799
00:36:43,376 --> 00:36:45,198
and helps maintaining that relationship long-term.

800
00:36:46,295 --> 00:36:52,916
A friend texted me this picture when he saw my name in the credits of Guacamelee 2.

801
00:36:54,116 --> 00:36:55,196
Give credit when it's appropriate.

802
00:36:55,216 --> 00:36:57,857
It means a lot to the people who help you and it will make people want to work with

803
00:36:57,877 --> 00:36:58,277
you again.

804
00:36:58,677 --> 00:37:01,938
It's been really mutually beneficial for me and having these connections is helping me

805
00:37:01,978 --> 00:37:02,178
now.

806
00:37:02,978 --> 00:37:06,399
And the credits can also actually be a great place to find the names of platform or publisher

807
00:37:06,419 --> 00:37:10,019
people you want to work with and then hunt them down online if you don't have a contact

808
00:37:10,059 --> 00:37:10,419
otherwise.

809
00:37:12,320 --> 00:37:14,080
So let's go on a journey together.

810
00:37:16,863 --> 00:37:20,366
This is Jenny. Jenny has a game. Jenny goes to GDC.

811
00:37:21,647 --> 00:37:24,809
Maybe she gets into GDC in some way that she can show her game.

812
00:37:26,010 --> 00:37:28,531
So then a person from a platform comes by

813
00:37:28,551 --> 00:37:33,034
to check out that game. So then Jenny can email them afterwards. Or maybe not.

814
00:37:33,094 --> 00:37:36,737
Maybe she didn't show to GDC and maybe Jenny has to go on Twitter and hunt them down.

815
00:37:38,278 --> 00:37:39,919
You know, Jenny's going to send a build of the game.

816
00:37:40,739 --> 00:37:44,742
Then maybe the platform person is going to be able to send them a dev kit back.

817
00:37:46,053 --> 00:37:47,914
And then Jenny's gonna keep them up to date

818
00:37:47,994 --> 00:37:49,535
with videos and screenshots

819
00:37:49,575 --> 00:37:51,176
and all the right ammunition we talked about.

820
00:37:51,436 --> 00:37:52,957
And then the platform person is gonna help

821
00:37:53,458 --> 00:37:54,378
release it into the world.

822
00:37:54,458 --> 00:37:56,640
And this workflow is just how it works most of the time.

823
00:37:56,720 --> 00:37:59,201
And I think it's important to recognize all these steps

824
00:37:59,241 --> 00:38:00,802
and have that dialogue.

825
00:38:03,284 --> 00:38:05,846
So, oh yeah, and then you should say thank you as well.

826
00:38:05,866 --> 00:38:06,326
That's important.

827
00:38:06,826 --> 00:38:09,328
We're gonna do a little case study with my friend,

828
00:38:10,048 --> 00:38:12,430
Mr. Phil Tobitoski right here from Young Horses.

829
00:38:12,450 --> 00:38:13,150
So,

830
00:38:16,095 --> 00:38:16,635
Yes, that's Phil.

831
00:38:17,215 --> 00:38:20,137
And I love, by the way, how the red on your jacket

832
00:38:20,177 --> 00:38:21,137
lines up with the tie.

833
00:38:21,157 --> 00:38:22,118
That's perfect.

834
00:38:22,258 --> 00:38:23,298
You have too many arms, though.

835
00:38:24,439 --> 00:38:26,380
So thanks to him for helping me with this session.

836
00:38:26,520 --> 00:38:27,881
I didn't know he was gonna come to this talk,

837
00:38:27,901 --> 00:38:29,222
so I'm glad he gets to see this in person.

838
00:38:32,632 --> 00:38:36,296
So back at GDC 2011, which is a long time ago,

839
00:38:37,156 --> 00:38:39,859
the original Octodad was an IGF nominee

840
00:38:39,939 --> 00:38:40,980
in the student showcase.

841
00:38:42,521 --> 00:38:44,563
Some assets that Phil Kamde sent me.

842
00:38:45,044 --> 00:38:46,005
And it didn't look quite as nice,

843
00:38:46,065 --> 00:38:47,486
but it was still goofy and fun.

844
00:38:47,526 --> 00:38:49,348
And I saw that the team was from DePaul University

845
00:38:49,368 --> 00:38:50,689
in Chicago, which is where I grew up.

846
00:38:51,390 --> 00:38:53,131
And I approached the team about it there,

847
00:38:53,191 --> 00:38:54,252
but it was sort of too early for them

848
00:38:54,272 --> 00:38:55,814
to consider doing something commercial with it,

849
00:38:55,874 --> 00:38:57,215
so we decided we'd just keep in touch.

850
00:38:58,427 --> 00:39:00,168
And then they showed the game later, a couple years later,

851
00:39:00,228 --> 00:39:01,869
at PAX East in the Indie Mega Booth.

852
00:39:02,209 --> 00:39:05,130
And everything looked a whole lot better as well,

853
00:39:05,150 --> 00:39:07,031
and they started pursuing it as a commercial product

854
00:39:07,552 --> 00:39:08,933
and as Young Horses as a new team.

855
00:39:09,533 --> 00:39:11,054
And the timing then meant that we could have

856
00:39:11,114 --> 00:39:12,935
early conversations with them about PlayStation 4.

857
00:39:14,296 --> 00:39:16,657
This is a nice quote that I can't see

858
00:39:16,757 --> 00:39:18,618
on either of these screens to read myself

859
00:39:18,678 --> 00:39:20,259
that was from a Polygon article

860
00:39:20,299 --> 00:39:21,420
where Phil said some kind things

861
00:39:21,480 --> 00:39:23,000
about just having this relationship

862
00:39:23,040 --> 00:39:24,361
where we could talk and I could help push

863
00:39:24,381 --> 00:39:25,222
for the game internally.

864
00:39:25,942 --> 00:39:26,803
But you can probably read that.

865
00:39:28,220 --> 00:39:30,581
So we sent them a PS4 development kit,

866
00:39:30,641 --> 00:39:32,482
which no one was supposed to post pictures of online,

867
00:39:32,502 --> 00:39:33,382
but somebody did.

868
00:39:34,583 --> 00:39:37,524
And they got the build running great in four weeks,

869
00:39:38,044 --> 00:39:39,784
which meant that we were able to showcase the game

870
00:39:40,004 --> 00:39:42,465
at, you know, in our E3 booth, which was huge.

871
00:39:43,146 --> 00:39:46,347
And it was even on stage as part of this Indie 8 event

872
00:39:46,387 --> 00:39:49,048
that we announced, which was a huge moment for PlayStation

873
00:39:49,128 --> 00:39:49,828
and for the team.

874
00:39:50,388 --> 00:39:51,869
And I think none of the big platforms

875
00:39:51,889 --> 00:39:53,089
had really done anything like this before,

876
00:39:53,169 --> 00:39:55,470
and there's actually not great screenshots of that

877
00:39:55,510 --> 00:39:56,330
somehow online either.

878
00:39:58,354 --> 00:40:00,089
And yeah, that's about it right there.

879
00:40:02,329 --> 00:40:06,451
So, you know, we ended up bringing them to over 26 different events.

880
00:40:06,851 --> 00:40:09,913
There's me and Phil and Adam Boyes, the old VP from PlayStation,

881
00:40:10,093 --> 00:40:12,094
and this costume that PlayStation made for them,

882
00:40:12,134 --> 00:40:15,295
which ended up being sort of one of the earlier, like, PS4 mascots almost.

883
00:40:16,476 --> 00:40:19,557
We had a private room for Octodad at the PlayStation 4 launch event,

884
00:40:19,598 --> 00:40:22,639
where press got to play the final PlayStation 4 hardware for the first time.

885
00:40:23,199 --> 00:40:25,600
And Sony Japan, you know, they were champions as well.

886
00:40:25,620 --> 00:40:28,462
They even helped localize the game and made a special logo for it.

887
00:40:29,843 --> 00:40:34,612
And so these guys have sold, I mean this is even out of date now, but after five years sold over two million units.

888
00:40:34,792 --> 00:40:36,876
Amazing. Let's give Phil a round of applause for that.

889
00:40:39,778 --> 00:40:44,599
And you'll notice too, only 17% of those sales are on PlayStation and 28% of the revenue.

890
00:40:44,619 --> 00:40:48,000
But I think that together we helped boost the profile of the game massively,

891
00:40:48,040 --> 00:40:50,980
which helped it go on and have this great tale across multiple platforms.

892
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:52,181
So a lot of that was really important.

893
00:40:52,901 --> 00:40:56,182
And I'll say, sorry Phil, I don't know if Octodad is a great game.

894
00:40:56,242 --> 00:40:57,222
Maybe you don't know either.

895
00:40:57,362 --> 00:41:00,923
And the team has had some fun with that themselves, despite the great sales.

896
00:41:01,523 --> 00:41:02,624
But I thought it was a great game.

897
00:41:03,284 --> 00:41:04,945
And it felt new to me and it had a lot of charm.

898
00:41:05,305 --> 00:41:06,346
And it made me want to fight for it.

899
00:41:06,366 --> 00:41:07,967
And I think that had a big impact on the game.

900
00:41:08,888 --> 00:41:10,449
And the team was always really easy to work with.

901
00:41:10,469 --> 00:41:11,970
They were a really responsive partner.

902
00:41:11,990 --> 00:41:13,230
And that made me want to work with them.

903
00:41:13,971 --> 00:41:15,912
And the timing worked out in their favor.

904
00:41:16,132 --> 00:41:18,754
And they didn't know that it would when they started talking to us.

905
00:41:18,794 --> 00:41:19,694
But we just kept in touch.

906
00:41:19,734 --> 00:41:21,435
And then an opportunity like this presented itself.

907
00:41:23,397 --> 00:41:24,117
Okay. More milk.

908
00:41:28,465 --> 00:41:32,227
So, a quick note on publishers, and we'll have some time for Q&A as well.

909
00:41:33,387 --> 00:41:36,169
So there's a lot of different indie publishers. This is an incomplete list.

910
00:41:37,349 --> 00:41:40,370
All of them have different priorities, different deal terms, different expertises.

911
00:41:40,951 --> 00:41:43,351
They also have different relationships with each of the big platforms.

912
00:41:43,972 --> 00:41:45,472
So I'd say make that part of your research.

913
00:41:45,973 --> 00:41:49,454
Is the publisher you want to work with released multiple games on a platform you want to be on?

914
00:41:50,332 --> 00:41:58,323
And they all have something in common, again, they're comprised of a bunch of different people with different tastes and you should think about them the same way you do your platform champion because they're going to have to fight for you as well.

915
00:41:59,044 --> 00:42:04,931
And almost no one you talk to initially is going to be the final decision maker. So there's always going to be this step of them fighting for your game internally.

916
00:42:06,740 --> 00:42:09,081
So I'd say also identify your needs from them.

917
00:42:09,181 --> 00:42:10,141
Is it localization?

918
00:42:10,261 --> 00:42:11,241
Is it QA?

919
00:42:11,341 --> 00:42:13,162
Is it help getting hardware?

920
00:42:13,822 --> 00:42:17,123
Is it just submitting the game and pressing the big red button?

921
00:42:18,104 --> 00:42:19,264
Is it marketing and PR?

922
00:42:19,444 --> 00:42:20,744
Or is it just money that you need?

923
00:42:20,764 --> 00:42:21,345
Is it just funding?

924
00:42:22,432 --> 00:42:25,454
Publishers tend to be very different from each other, more so than platforms.

925
00:42:26,354 --> 00:42:30,457
Helping to decide exactly what you want beforehand is really helpful.

926
00:42:31,057 --> 00:42:34,419
And with regards to funding, you know, is the money recoupable, is it not?

927
00:42:34,479 --> 00:42:35,579
Do they recoup at different rates?

928
00:42:36,320 --> 00:42:39,101
Some recoup the marketing and event spend that they put towards it,

929
00:42:39,181 --> 00:42:41,923
or want the right of refusal, or to own an IP.

930
00:42:42,343 --> 00:42:44,284
And these are all different negotiating knobs to turn.

931
00:42:44,304 --> 00:42:46,805
And usually when you have to turn one up, you'll have to turn another one down.

932
00:42:47,605 --> 00:42:49,186
And no one's going to give you exactly what you want.

933
00:42:50,247 --> 00:42:54,368
I'd say also in my experience you can usually tell from someone's response time how they're going to be to work with.

934
00:42:54,408 --> 00:42:57,450
Just because they're slow doesn't mean it's bad, but it's a consideration of working with them.

935
00:42:59,370 --> 00:43:01,832
And the same key elements are the same when you're talking to potential publishers.

936
00:43:01,912 --> 00:43:07,814
So the things we talked about making the right game, making it findable, arming your champion, and keeping your champion.

937
00:43:11,359 --> 00:43:14,942
I reached out to my friend Brandon Sinclair from Games Industry.

938
00:43:15,262 --> 00:43:17,023
He's been a journalist for over 15 years.

939
00:43:17,904 --> 00:43:24,268
He reminded me that press like to lurk and that if you post things with the game dev

940
00:43:24,288 --> 00:43:26,970
hashtag and other developer communities, press are often watching.

941
00:43:27,570 --> 00:43:29,352
And if a journalist has awareness of a game already,

942
00:43:29,372 --> 00:43:31,735
it's going to be a lot easier pitching them to cover it.

943
00:43:32,937 --> 00:43:34,539
And think about what's interesting about your game.

944
00:43:34,579 --> 00:43:35,781
Is it in your pitch?

945
00:43:37,062 --> 00:43:37,843
Is it the game mechanics?

946
00:43:37,863 --> 00:43:39,085
Is it the topic or the theme?

947
00:43:39,125 --> 00:43:40,266
Is it your personal story?

948
00:43:40,326 --> 00:43:42,549
Is it the development method, something non-traditional?

949
00:43:43,590 --> 00:43:45,152
And targeted outreach is important too.

950
00:43:45,192 --> 00:43:48,455
I think reaching out just totally broadly to press won't get you the best results.

951
00:43:49,035 --> 00:43:53,159
Consider the audience for your game in which press outlets, you know, target that audience.

952
00:43:53,980 --> 00:43:58,544
You know, so Double Fine, I've talked to them about how they targeted influencers and streamers for Gang Beasts,

953
00:43:58,644 --> 00:44:03,588
but, you know, for everything, more of an arcade, they targeted Polygon and leaned hard into both of those things.

954
00:44:04,349 --> 00:44:05,469
And you can think about targeting press

955
00:44:05,489 --> 00:44:06,610
who have covered similar games.

956
00:44:07,450 --> 00:44:10,011
So if you're making a game for niche hobbyists,

957
00:44:10,152 --> 00:44:11,912
maybe you don't want to target games press.

958
00:44:11,952 --> 00:44:13,533
Maybe you should find where your audience is.

959
00:44:14,834 --> 00:44:16,935
Maybe your game about quilting would

960
00:44:16,955 --> 00:44:19,616
be better targeted at a quilting magazine than Game Informer.

961
00:44:20,777 --> 00:44:21,897
And do your research.

962
00:44:21,937 --> 00:44:24,158
Don't reach out to an outlet asking them to review your game

963
00:44:24,318 --> 00:44:25,299
if they don't do reviews.

964
00:44:26,441 --> 00:44:27,441
